##A job you can't get back, a business you can't start: "I'm going to work every Monday. "

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

They all have small worries, worries, felicitations and reflections

The epidemic came like a flood, and no one could escape it.

The question of when full normalcy will return is one of common concern. Unsealing the news of the resumption of work continued to spread, the flowers of the park opened, many cars on the road up, the city resurrected. Some have returned to their workshops and workstations, and many more have long since started telecommuting.

But some industries have been hard hit to recover from.

The first to go is the tertiary sector of the economy. Films, restaurants, tourism, entertainment, education and training, financial services, real estate, sports, transportation... just a glimpse of the leopard, according to research data from economist Ren Zepin's team, the country lost 7 billion yuan at the box office, 500 billion yuan at restaurants and retail outlets, and 500 billion yuan in the tourism market, all of which accounted for more than 1 trillion yuan, or 4.6 percent of the country's GDP of 21.8 trillion yuan in the first quarter of 2019.

There are countless specific individuals behind the vast data.

China Newsweek recently interviewed four ordinary people affected by the epidemic who were still unable to return to work. Their living conditions, economic levels, industries and regions are all different, but compared with the great joys and sorrows of big business, they all have minor worries, worries, felicitations and reflections, under the pressure of life, self-mockery "can not lie down to make money but to spend money lying down" .

Feng Shoushou, Beijing, teacher of Training Institution

I was thrilled when I received a voice call from my immediate superior.

She told me this afternoon (March 1) that she would hold a conference call to arrange her future work. I'm so happy. Wow, it's back to work! As a result, at 6 p.m. , she told me that due to the outbreak, Beijing had ordered all education and training institutions to stop offline training until the end of April at the earliest. The company has no income for these two months, so during the wage suspension, social security also suspended, my salary until February.

The company I work for is very small. It has three parts: study abroad, education and training. We do not have a wide range of online channels, mainly offline training. I am a teacher, teach adult toefl, ielts basic English.

On January 29, I came to Beijing from my hometown in Luoyang. It was bad, and I was wearing sunglasses, a hat, disposable medical gloves, and alcohol. It was crowded, and the seats on the high-speed train weren't ready.

On the same day before the high-speed rail I also asked the leadership whether to postpone the work, she said that did not receive the notice. On the seventh day of the New Year, I ran to the office without notice of the delay in resuming work. And I didn't see anyone. Another training institution on the same floor is so lonely, only the principal is inside.

The director never gave us an accurate description. I've missed a few more, and every Monday I'm getting ready to go to work.

I've been back in Beijing for over a month. The first two weeks I also did the online course, and then the online course channel cooperation expired, let me do the overseas study consultation as well as the whole information and so on very tedious work.

This more than a month I buy food to cook, where dare not go, I am afraid of which day call me to work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A street view taken by Feng Shoushou while he was out shopping on February 7

In our industry, most teachers work from home, and all offline courses become online. But online classes are limited, online platforms are few and far between, and courses can not be arranged. So a lot of line off class, especially one person several thousand dollars class time fee big class class also was cancelled. There's a lot of us down here in Haidian District.

The leader said to me on the phone, "you can look for a job, we don't blame you, but you are welcome to return to work. ". I was defenseless. I couldn't believe it. I was overwhelmed! She also said that any difficulties can find her, no money can find you? !

I've never done this before. I graduated last year. I don't have much savings. Living in Beijing is expensive, with a monthly rent of at least 5,000 yuan, let alone in Haidian District. It was hard to find a job during the outbreak, and I didn't know what to do.

My first reaction was whether I should tell my family whether I should leave Beijing or not. My mom calls me at night to see how I'm doing at work, but I'm afraid to tell her. My family has not returned to work, the family has no income.

Qiu Qiu, a fourth-tier city in Guangdong, makeup artist

I'm having a nervous breakdown. I can't go out there.

Time passed so quickly that it seemed to be dark before waking up. I now sleep at home every day, sometimes sleep until 1:00 pm, up to watch mobile phone drama, boring began to cook, and then boring time for health, a gap is not let up. Picking Your fingernails, pulling out your split ends, pulling out all the wrong ones.

Always wanted to get out and work. We may not be able to resume work in this industry until the summer of April or May. Since February, I haven't had a single makeup artist around.

I can't make any money for six months. I have to spend it. This evening I went to the supermarket and bought some snacks, eggs, milk and some dragon fruit. It cost me one hundred and fifty bucks.

New Year's was a busy time. January and February are the peak season, because there are more festivals, and Valentine's Day. I used to work in the nail shop in the pedestrian street, until 10:00 pm until the unified closed, New Year's Eve, the first two will work. How many guests? That is countless Luo, just do a nail I a person every day to do about 10, some style complex to do about 2 hours.

Starting last November, I worked with a star hotel to make up 20 or 30 foot massage technicians. I only had to go four hours a day, and the rest of the time I worked part time at my old Nail Salon, as well as in photographic studio, at the studio, and as a makeup artist for Taobao's print models.

But affected by the epidemic, the hotel was empty in about half of the people. Originally the first day of the New Year asked me to go back to work, then the city issued a notice to suspend the city's cultural, sports and entertainment business activities, until now, I was waiting at home.

At the end of January, some of my peers were working, but it got worse and worse, and in February they gradually quit. I added the makeup group, so far there is not a need to call for help ah cover the shift AH, no one.

I've worked 10 years as a makeup artist for four years, and I've never taken a vacation this long.

It's a good thing my husband's still at work, or he wouldn't be able to afford it. I was going to save my money this year. I had the idea of having a baby in the past two years, and then I could open my own shop. But maybe now. I like it, too. Just wait till I get back to work.

Xia Haoyan, restaurant owner, Shanghai

I'm optimistic.

I've been a caterer for 13 years, I've been in a lot of places, but I've always done it for someone else. Now I run a small restaurant in Nanqiao, Xingtang County, Fengxian District, that specializes in Wontons, the equivalent of Sha County snacks. It's not a big store. It's only 30 square meters. It opened June 2nd, 2018, and I invested with a friend. So far, in addition to our two bosses, there's a clerk.

I'm a cashier, a cook, and a delivery boy myself. There are few riders at the end of the year. If you're near, you can send them yourself. Sometimes I get bored and send someone else's takeout to make extra money.

The store opened at 5:30 a.m. and didn't close until after 3:00 the next morning. The three of US took turns coming and going early. But I don't feel tired. It's all hands on deck. Do it for yourself. Go for it. The most tiring time is when there is no business.

The second half of the year is the peak season, especially during the summer vacation. The beginning of the year is off-season, especially catch up with the epidemic, now is zero income, but rent, electricity bills have to pay. The rent is 60,000 a year, and this year's rent is due in May. I don't know if I can lower it.

We normally start on the eighth day. On the fourth day of the New Year, I came from my hometown to a friend's house in Zhejiang. I originally planned to play for three days, but I didn't realize that the epidemic was serious and I was stuck here. When the resumption of work is not sure, to Shanghai to stay at home isolation for 14 days.

I don't expect to be open until late March, and then I expect to be able to do takeout instead of eating at the restaurant, which is expected to be a 90% drop in revenue.

I'm sure there'll be some takeout. Just do your own surveillance. I ordered a lot of things in advance to re-open for business, the recent delivery has arrived.

Zhang Feng, Xi'an, Shaanxi, tour guide

None of the guides I know are open.

Tourism is off-season every winter, and I only took one job in January. Travel Agency bosses have more to lose. They have sales, finances and so on.

The biggest impact for me was that I gained 10 pounds and had no money. Many people in the circle of friends are doing wechat business, and some old guides in Douyin to do live broadcast.

My rent is normal, the landlord is very good, in the past few years have not raised the rent. Unfortunately, I missed the golden period to buy a house in Xi'an, because I have been struggling, after all, the pressure of mortgage. We're in a special line of work. We get paid on the spot. For a guy like me who made $300 today, I'd have to spend $200 to $250 to save a little. Not to mention a lot of post-'90s and post-'00s are moonstruck.

But the impact on the tourism industry as a whole has been enormous. Some news reports say the outbreak has hit the tourism industry the hardest, with the country's tourism industry expected to lose nearly 3 trillion yuan this year. That's not an exaggeration, but it could turn out to be even bigger. Tourism industry belongs to the tertiary sector of the economy, there are eating, living, travel, tourism, shopping, entertainment, to solve the employment scope is very broad.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"February 2" of this year's Day in Xi'an Datang night city map / Shaanxi Provincial Culture and Tourism Department official website

On December twenty-eight, our team was canceled. We are not normal Chinese New Year holiday, peak period in the second to sixth day, every day will be very busy, basic will not idle down. One day I took a guest out at 7:00 in the morning and didn't come home until 12:00 at night. Spring Festival tourists, the year before last, around the fourth day of the Lunar New Year, I took a taxi home after work in the evening, the master listen to me say is Shaanxi dialect, with me, "you are the only local I pull these days. ".

My family has a hotel in town, and we have a normal holiday every year. It's still closed this year. It must have had an effect on the family. Suddenly there was no income.

The current staff of the travel agency is already at work, but what does the tour guide do without tourists. If our industry returns to work on a large scale across the country, it will be in the second half of the year. For example, you usually love to go to a certain restaurant confirmed a case, but the follow-up did not report, I asked you, you dare to go? Besides, who wants to go out when everyone's income goes down after the epidemic?

Some of the scenic spots in Xi'an are not open at present. I mainly travel within the province, half of which are family study tours. During the normal school year, the beginning of the semester, the end of the semester, March, November, the parents will take annual leave with their children, as part of the course. But the students have not yet started school, the child's parents are also affected, as before so generous take money to go out with the Child?

Even if things return to normal, I have concerns about Xi'an's tourism industry. There are no bus parks outside Giant Wild Goose Pagoda, no parking signs on Xi'an Road, no parking in front of small hotels. City and provincial documents differ on the parking of tour buses alone. In this context, I do not know what will happen after the impact of the epidemic in Xi'an tourism.

My family is recommending a career change, but I'd like to take another look.
